  "What does 'back substitution' mean in Gaussian elimination?": "",
  "Reversing all row operations performed": "",
  "Solving for variables starting from the last equation and working upward": "",
  "Replacing the augmented matrix with the original system": "",
  "Substituting rows back into their original positions": "",
  "After reaching row echelon form, back substitution solves for each variable starting from the bottom row (which has only one unknown) and substituting back into higher rows.": "",
  "After Gaussian elimination, the matrix is [[1, -1, 2, 4], [0, 2, -1, 3], [0, 0, 3, 9]]. What is z?": "",
  "-3": "",
  "1": "",
  "9": "",
  "The third row gives 3z = 9, so z = 3. Then back substitution can determine y and x.": "",
  "How many elementary row operations are the three types used in Gaussian elimination?": "",
  "4": "",
  "The three types are: (1) swap two rows, (2) multiply a row by a nonzero scalar, and (3) add a scalar multiple of one row to another row.": "",
