  "What is a 'pivot' in Gaussian elimination?": "",
  "The first nonzero entry in a row used to eliminate entries below it": "",
  "The constant in the augmented column": "",
  "Any entry on the main diagonal": "",
  "The largest entry in the matrix": "",
  "A pivot is the leading nonzero entry in a row during elimination. It is used as the reference element to create zeros in all entries directly below it in the same column.": "",
  "What does the term 'forward elimination' refer to in Gaussian elimination?": "",
  "Solving variables from the top row first": "",
  "The phase of creating zeros below each pivot to reach row echelon form": "",
  "Adding new equations to the system": "",
  "Verifying the solution by substituting forward": "",
  "Forward elimination is the first phase of Gaussian elimination where row operations systematically create zeros below each pivot, working from left to right and top to bottom.": "",
  "What is 'partial pivoting' in the context of Gaussian elimination?": "",
  "Using only part of the pivot row for elimination": "",
  "Dividing the pivot by 2 before proceeding": "",
  "Skipping columns that have small entries": "",
  "Choosing the row with the largest absolute value in the pivot column and swapping it to the pivot position": "",
  "Partial pivoting selects the row below (and including) the current pivot row that has the largest absolute value in the pivot column, then swaps it into position. This improves numerical stability.": "",
  "What does 'row echelon form' mean?": "",
  "All entries below and above each pivot are zero": "",
  "A form where all diagonal entries are 1": "",
  "A form where all entries below each pivot are zero and each pivot is to the right of the pivot in the row above": "",
  "A form where the matrix is symmetric": "",
  "In row echelon form, all entries below each leading entry (pivot) are zero, each pivot is strictly to the right of the pivot above it, and any all-zero rows are at the bottom.": "",
  "What is a 'multiplier' in Gaussian elimination?": "",
  "The scalar factor used to eliminate an entry below a pivot": "",
  "The number of row operations performed": "",
  "The determinant of the coefficient matrix": "",
  "The product of all pivots": "",
  "The multiplier m_ij = a_ij / a_jj is the factor by which the pivot row j is multiplied before subtracting it from row i to create a zero in position (i, j).": "",
  "What does it mean for a matrix to be in 'upper triangular form'?": "",
  "Only the diagonal entries are nonzero": "",
  "The matrix has the shape of a triangle": "",
  "All entries above the main diagonal are zero": "",
  "All entries below the main diagonal are zero": "",
  "An upper triangular matrix has all entries below the main diagonal equal to zero. Gaussian elimination aims to produce this staircase pattern of zeros.": "",
  "What is a 'pivot column' in Gaussian elimination?": "",
  "The last column of the augmented matrix": "",
  "Any column that contains only zeros": "",
  "The column with the largest entries": "",
  "A column that contains a pivot position": "",
  "A pivot column is any column of the coefficient matrix that contains a leading entry (pivot) in row echelon form. Variables corresponding to pivot columns are called basic variables.": "",
  "What does the term 'row equivalent' mean for two matrices?": "",
  "They have identical entries": "",
  "One can be obtained from the other by a sequence of elementary row operations": "",
  "They have the same determinant": "",
  "They have the same dimensions": "",
  "Two matrices are row equivalent if one can be transformed into the other through a finite sequence of elementary row operations. Row equivalent augmented matrices represent systems with the same solution set.": "",
  "What is a 'free variable' that can appear during Gaussian elimination?": "",
  "A variable whose column has no pivot, so it can take any value": "",
  "A variable that equals zero": "",
  "A variable that appears in only one equation": "",
  "A variable that has been eliminated from the system": "",
  "A free variable corresponds to a non-pivot column. Since there is no leading entry in that column, the variable is not determined by the system and can be assigned any real value.": "",
  "What does 'numerical stability' mean in the context of Gaussian elimination?": "",
  "The algorithm always produces integer results": "",
  "The algorithm terminates in a fixed number of steps": "",
  "Rounding errors during computation do not cause large inaccuracies in the final answer": "",
  "The matrix entries remain constant throughout the procedure": "",
  "Numerical stability means that small rounding errors introduced during floating-point computations do not amplify into large errors in the solution. Techniques like partial pivoting help maintain stability.": "",
  "An aerospace engineer models the lift, drag, and weight balance of an aircraft using 3 equations in 3 unknowns. She writes the augmented matrix [[2, 1, -1, 8], [4, 3, -1, 18], [2, 2, 1, 13]]. After subtracting 2 times R1 from R2 and subtracting R1 from R3, what is the new R2?": "",
  "[0, 1, 1, 2]": "",
  "[0, 1, -1, 2]": "",
  "[0, 2, -1, 10]": "",
  "[0, 0, 2, 5]": "",
  "R2 - 2R1 = [4-4, 3-2, -1-(-2), 18-16] = [0, 1, 1, 2]. This creates a zero below the first pivot.": "",
  "A financial analyst models quarterly revenue flows with the system x + y + z = 12, 2x + 3y + z = 20, and x - y + 2z = 9. After Gaussian elimination, she obtains [[1, 1, 1, 12], [0, 1, -1, -4], [0, 0, 3, 9]]. What is z?": "",
  "12": "",
  "-4": "",
  "From row 3: 3z = 9, so z = 3. Back substitution then gives y = -4 + z = -4 + 3 = -1, and x = 12 - y - z = 12 - (-1) - 3 = 10.": "",
  "A chemist is balancing a reaction and obtains the augmented matrix [[1, -2, 1, 0], [0, 1, -3, 0], [0, 0, 0, 0]] after elimination. How many free variables are there?": "",
  "0": "",
  "There are 3 variables and 2 pivots (in columns 1 and 2), so there is 3 - 2 = 1 free variable (x3). The all-zero row is consistent (0 = 0) and does not add a constraint.": "",
  "An electrical engineer is solving a circuit with 4 mesh equations. During Gaussian elimination, the pivot in position (2,2) turns out to be zero, but position (3,2) has the value -5. What should she do?": "",
  "Set the (2,2) entry to 1 manually": "",
  "Swap rows 2 and 3, then continue elimination": "",
  "Declare the system has no solution": "",
  "Delete column 2 from the matrix": "",
  "When a pivot is zero, swap the current row with a row below it that has a nonzero entry in the pivot column. Swapping rows 2 and 3 places -5 in the pivot position, allowing elimination to continue.": "",
  "A logistics company models shipping routes with the system: 3x + y = 15, 6x + 2y = 30, and x + y = 7. After Gaussian elimination the manager gets [[3, 1, 15], [0, 0, 0], [0, 2/3, 2]]. What does the zero row tell her?": "",
  "The system has no solution": "",
  "The second equation was a scalar multiple of the first, providing no new information": "",
  "One of the variables must equal zero": "",
  "The system has exactly three solutions": "",
  "The equation 6x + 2y = 30 is exactly 2 times the first equation 3x + y = 15, so it is redundant. After elimination it reduces to [0, 0 | 0], confirming it adds no new constraint.": "",
  "A researcher in materials science has a 4x4 system. After Gaussian elimination, she obtains pivots of 2, -3, 1, and 4 on the diagonal. She needs the determinant. What is it?": "",
  "10": "",
  "-24": "",
  "24": "",
